thread.title_full: Brad Biggs' NFL power rankings - Chicago Tribune

author: Brad Biggs
title: Brad Biggs' NFL power rankings - Chicago Tribune
text:
Previous rank in parentheses.
1. Patriots 5-0 (1) : Properly inflated footballs proved to be no problem for Tom Brady against the Colts this time around.
2. Bengals 6-0 (3) : Marvin Lewis the early leader for coach of the year.
3. Packers 6-0 (2) : With a week off, Green Bay looks to get running back Eddie Lacy healed from an ankle injury and back in shape.
4. Panthers 5-0 (7) : With Falcons nipping at their heels, Carolina just keeps finding ways to win.
5. Broncos 6-0 (4) : Criticism of Peyton Manning isn't going to faze Broncos as long as they keep stacking wins.
6. Steelers 4-2 (9) : This team will be pretty scary when it gets healthy. Landry Jones expected to get first career start Sunday at Kansas City.
7. Cardinals 4-2 (6) : Couldn't get it done in Bruce Arians' return to Pittsburgh and now AFC North tour continues with Ravens, Browns up next.
8. Jets 4-1 (8) : Wonder if Darrelle Revis will wish he was back on the other sideline Sunday at Gillette Stadium against the Patriots.
9. Falcons 5-1 (5) : After loss in New Orleans, soft schedule continues with Titans, Bucs and 49ers next up.
10. Vikings 3-2 (13) : Emergence of rookie wide receiver Stefon Diggs worth watching in Norv Turner's offense.
11. Eagles 3-3 (17) : Two straight wins is all it takes to go from the outhouse to the penthouse in the NFC East.
12. Rams 2-3 (15) : Hearing on possible relocation to L.A. set for next Tuesday and it will be interesting to see how fans show up with two home games coming up.
13. Seahawks 2-4 (10) : So much for the return of safety Kam Chancellor righting what was wrong with this defense.
14. Giants 3-3 (11) : Eli Manning completed his first 10 passes against the Eagles Monday night and then fell apart. New York can't win without him playing at a high level.
15. Colts 3-3 (14) : Best photoshop of bungled fake punt by Chuck Pagano used images of Beavis and Butthead.
16. Bills 3-3 (12) : This defense hasn't been measuring up to Rex Ryan's standards.
17. Cowboys 2-3 (19) : Eagles and Giants were so unimpressive Monday night surely Jerry Jones can resist temptation to rush Dez Bryant back on the field.
18. Chargers 2-4 (16) : Philip Rivers on pace to pass for NFL-record 5,643 yards but they've been just bad enough to lose series of close games.
19. Dolphins 2-3 (24) : Kudos to interim coach Dan Campbell for lighting a fire under his team. Just realize Titans aren't on the schedule every week.
20. Browns 2-4 (22) : Tempted to believe progress is being made here but Rams, Cardinals and Bengals in next three weeks will provide better gauge.
21. Raiders 2-3 (21) : Ken Norton Jr. has done a nice job running defense and now must replace play as well as leadership of Justin Tuck.
22. Bears 2-4 (18) : Return of Alshon Jeffery gives Adam Gase much more to consider as Bears map out final 10 games during bye week.
23. 49ers 2-4 (28) : They're building a little bit of confidence just in time to see how they measure up against the struggling Seahawks on Thursday.
24. Saints 2-4 (30) : Defense is ranked last in the league but it was good enough to catch an overhyped Falcons bunch.
25. Redskins 2-4 (20) : One of these weeks Jay Gruden will admit the reality that his team needs a quarterback.
26. Buccaneers 2-3 (27) : With road game at Redskins on horizon, just one more victory needed to eclipse their 2014 total.
27. Texans 2-4 (29) : Brian Hoyer named starter again and whatever possessed Bill O'Brien to play Ryan Mallett escapes us.
28. Ravens 1-5 (23) : Worst start in franchise history could be worse after Monday's tussle with Cardinals in Arizona.
29. Lions 1-5 (32) : Matthew Stafford showed some resolve with four touchdown passes against Bears.
30. Chiefs 1-5 (26) : Andy Reid is adamant he's not going to hand over play-calling duties.
31. Titans 1-4 (25) : Pass defense one of the few bright spots especially with Marcus Mariota dealing with knee sprain.
32. Jaguars 1-5 (31) : Sending this team to London is no way to globally promote the product.
